        en: `
            <h1>Onam: The Grand Homecoming Festival of Kerala</h1>
            <p>Onam is the most significant harvest festival of Kerala, India. It's a vibrant, ten-day-long celebration that marks the homecoming of the legendary King Mahabali. The festival is a celebration of prosperity, abundance, and the rich cultural heritage of Kerala.</p>
            
            <h2>Why is Onam Celebrated? The Legend of King Mahabali</h2>
            <p>The festival commemorates the Vamana avatar of Vishnu and the subsequent homecoming of the benevolent demon King Mahabali. According to legend, King Mahabali was a wise and generous ruler, and his reign was a golden era of peace and prosperity. The gods grew jealous of his popularity and sent Vamana (Vishnu in the form of a dwarf Brahmin) to test him. Vamana asked for three paces of land, and the generous king agreed. Vamana then grew to a cosmic size, covering the earth and heavens in two steps. For the third step, Mahabali offered his own head. Impressed by his devotion, Vishnu granted him a boon to visit his beloved subjects once every year. Onam celebrates this annual return of King Mahabali.</p>
            
            <h3>How is it Celebrated?</h3>
            <p>Onam is marked by a series of colorful rituals and festivities. The main attractions include the intricate 'Pookalam' (floral carpets), the grand 'Onam Sadhya' (a multi-course vegetarian feast served on a banana leaf), the thrilling 'Vallam Kali' (snake boat races), and traditional dance forms like 'Thiruvathira Kali' and the spectacular 'Pulikali' (tiger dance).</p>

            <h2>Where is Onam Celebrated?</h2>
            <p>Onam is celebrated with great fervor by people of all communities in Kerala and by the Malayali diaspora across the world. It is a time for family reunions, feasting, and engaging in cultural activities that showcase the spirit of the state.</p>
        `,
